Yes, you can use foreach loop to get the rows in the sheet...

However, I would add...

...that you should probably use a builder-like pattern.

Here is MVCE of the class, as well as a util method that may come in handy. I asked Phind AI to adapt it from my Groovy version (which is so much cleaner), so please take it with grain of salt...


## The `CustomerSheetReader`

```
public class CustomerSheetReader implements AutoCloseable {
	private Workbook spreadsheet;
	private Sheet sheet;
	// any other fields, e.g. input streams

	public CustomerSheetReader() {
		// open the workbook and initialize the sheet
	}

	public CustomerSheetReader(Sheet sheet) {
		this.sheet = sheet;
	}

	public List&lt;Customer&gt; read() { 
		List&lt;Customer&gt; customerModels = new ArrayList&lt;CustomerSheet&gt;();

		final int lastNonEmptyRowNum = SpreadsheetUtils.GetLastNonEmptyRowNum(this.sheet);
		for (int rowNum = 1; rowNum &lt;= lastNonEmptyRowNum; rowNum++) { 
			customerModels.add(this.createModelFromRow(sheet.getRow(rowNum)));
		}

		return customerModels;
	}

	public Customer createModelFromRow(Row row) {
		Customer model = new Customer();

		for (int cellIdx = 0; cellIdx &lt; row.getLastCellNum(); cellIdx++)
			model = this.buildModelFromCell(row.getCell(cellIdx), model);

		return model;
	}

	// TODO: we could make this better, by moving away from indices, and using dictionaries and/or callbacks instead. The latter would make the following code so much cleaner
	private Customer buildModelFromCell(Cell cell, Customer model) {
		switch (cell.getColumnIndex()) { 
			default:
				throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Cannot build model from cell having column index &quot; + cell.getColumnIndex() + &quot;!&quot;);

			case 0: 
				int id;
				if (cell.getType().equals(CellType.NUMERIC))
					id = cell.getNumericCellValue();
				else 
					id = Integer.parseInt(cell.getStringCellValue());

				model.number = id;
				return model;
			case 1:
				model.CustomerName = cell.getStringCellValue();
				return model;
			case 2: 
				model.CustomerLatest = cell.getStringCellValue();
				return model;
			case 3:
				// TODO: you may face issue with the string being of type numeric instead of type string. I leave handling of that up to you
				model.CustomerYear = cell.getStringCellValue();
				return model;

		}
	}

	@Override
	public void close() {
		// close the workbook and any input streams
	}
}
```

## The util method

In Groovy, I have this as one-liner thanks to its built-in callback-based `findLastIndexOf`. Here is Java version (DISCLAIMER: I have not tested this)

```
// SOURCE: https://www.phind.com/search?cache=s5oul8pz6nrmdz9lj49rh3o0
public class SpreadsheetUtils {
    public static int GetLastNonEmptyRowNum(Sheet sheet) {
        // Iterate over the rows from the end towards the beginning
        for (int i = sheet.getLastRowNum(); i &gt;= 0; i--) {
            Row row = sheet.getRow(i);

            // If the row is null, continue to the next iteration
            if (row == null) {
                continue;
            }

            // Check if the row is non-empty
            if (row.getLastCellNum() != -1) {
                // Return the index of the non-empty row
                return i;
            }
        }

        // If no non-empty row is found, return -1
        return -1;
    }
}

```

## Thoughts

If you don&#39;t want to use the helper method, you can do what @Abhijeet has suggested: use for-each loop instead.

