The straightforward way is do what you do, but use `&lt;=` to invoke only methods you need depending on the given `step`.

```java
public void process(Document document, int step) {
    if (step &lt;= 0)
        this.processHeader(document);
    if (step &lt;= 1)
        this.processContent(document);
    if (step &lt;= 2)
        this.processFooter(document);
    
    // ...
}
```

How much refactoring can you do?  Adding on to Oleg&#39;s answer, another approach would be to move the `if` to the step method so the `process` method body becomes fluent. Also change `step` type to an enum, along with some name changes to clarify intent.
 

    enum DocumentProcessStep {
       PROCESS_HEADER,
       PROCESS_CONTENT,
       PROCESS_FOOTER,
    }
    
    class DocumentProcesser {

        public void process(Document doucment, DocumentProcessStep startWith) {
            processHeaderIfNeeded(document, startWith)
                .processContentIfNeeded(document, startWith)
                .processFooterIfNeeded(document, startWith);
        }

        private DocumentProcesser processContentIfNeeded(Document document, DocumentProcessStep step) 
        {
            if (step &lt;= DocumentProcessStep.PROCESS_HEADER ) {
               // ...
            }
 
           return this;
        }

        private DocumentProcesser processHeaderIfNeeded(Document document, DocumentProcessStep step) 
        {
            if (step &lt;= DocumentProcessStep.PROCESS_CONTENT ) {
               // ...
            }
 
           return this;
        }

        private DocumentProcesser processFooterIfNeeded(Document document, DocumentProcessStep step) 
        {
            if (step &lt;= DocumentProcessStep.PROCESS_FOOTER) {
               // ...
            }
 
           return this;
        }
    }

Each step can be represented as an action/command. I will use `Consumer&lt;Document&gt;`, but you can use your own abstraction, if it fits the scenario better. Since the order matters, use a collection like `List` to keep the required actions in order.
```
List&lt;Consumer&lt;Document&gt;&gt; actions = List.of(
        document -&gt; processHeader(document),
        document -&gt; processContent(document),
        document -&gt; processFooter(document)
);
```
A processor class handling the actions:
```
public class Processor {

  private final List&lt;Consumer&lt;Document&gt;&gt; actions;

  public Processor(List&lt;Consumer&lt;Document&gt;&gt; actions) {
    this.actions = actions;
  }

  public void process(Document document, int step) {
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; actions.size(); i++) {
      Consumer&lt;Document&gt; action = actions.get(i);
      action.accept(document);
      int currentStep = i + 1;
      if (currentStep == step) {
        return;
      }
    }
  }
}
```
It may be appropriate to make the step of each `Action` as part of the API in order to avoid working with the indexes as in this example.
```
public interface Action {
  
  void accept(Document document);
  int getStep();
}
```

&gt; _&quot;How to control the execution based on logical input parameter in a method in Java ...\
&gt;\
&gt; ... What could be cleaner, readable and easily maintainable way to do this? ...&quot;_

You&#39;re asking for many different re-factors.

_Logically_, you can use a _[class structure](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/index.html)_ to distribute _document_.\
And, _[methods](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/methods.html)_ to _encapsulate_ the _processes_.

Here is an example.

```java
class Process {
    Document document;

    void a() {
        processHeader(document);
    }

    void b() {
        a();
        processContent(document);
    }

    void c() {
        b();
        processFooter(document);
    }
}
```

A _&quot;cleaner, readable and easily maintainable way&quot;_, would be to just format the code.

```java
void process(Document document, int step) {
    this.processHeader(document);
    if(step==1) return;
    this.processContent(document);
    if(step==2) return;
    this.processFooter(document);
}
```

I guess you could adjust the _[relational operators](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/operators.html)_, although you&#39;re currently using an &quot;early-return&quot; design, which is actually more _logical_.

```java
void process(Document document, int step) {
    if (step &gt; 0) this.processHeader(document);
    if (step &gt; 1) this.processContent(document);
    if (step &gt; 2) this.processFooter(document);
}
```

Realistically, you&#39;re looking for an _[agile design principle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agile_software_development)_.\
Keep in mind, these can be confusing, and they are not tailored for every abstraction.

It&#39;s still not clear what&#39;s wrong with your code or why you don&#39;t like `switch`, for example, but if your sole question is how not to use &quot;if-then-else&quot;, then I&#39;d have used `switch expression`s, if you&#39;re using Java 14 or higher:

```java
public int process(Document document, int step) {
    this.processHeader(document);

    return switch (step) {
        case 1 -&gt;  //expression #1;
        case 2 -&gt;  //expression #2;
        case 3 -&gt;  //expression #3;
        default -&gt; //expression or throw
    };
}
```

If you&#39;re having Java version &lt; 14, then go with simple `switch`, as:

```java
public int process(Document document, int step) {
    this.processHeader(document);

    switch (step) {
        case 1:  //return code #1;
        case 2:  //return code #2;
        default: //return code #3;
    }
}
```

